    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-09-28T12:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-09-28T12:00:00-05:00" n="544"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d544">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">822.00 Revolutions/70: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Ecuador</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gonzalez</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Quito</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-09-28T12:00:00-05:00"
                            >September 28, 1935—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received 12:33 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>45. In view of certain election of conservative candidate the President and the
                    entire Cabinet resigned yesterday. The armed forces took over and delegated the
                    power to Federico Paez. Constitution of 1906 substituted in so far as it does
                    not conflict with reforms contemplated. Paez a Socialist has announced intention
                    to initiate immediately downright social reforms. Congress unofficially informed
                    that it has been dissolved.</p>
                <p>Since the government established is a <hi rend="italic">de facto</hi> military
                    dictatorship the question of recognition arises. Majority of armed forces
                    excepting Guayaquil appear favorable but dissension is growing. Left bloc is not
                    satisfied and is advocating designation of Larrea Alba<note n="28"
                        xml:id="d544fn28">Col. Luis Larrea Alba, deported in February 1935 by order
                        of President Velasco Ibarra.</note> as dictator. Conservatives are
                    intransigent and are preparing opposition. Attitude of Guayaquil is serious in
                    view of Larrea’s arrival there tomorrow. Potentialities of situation are
                    extremely disquieting.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Gonzalez</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
